answers.body_markdown:
There is no way to use `componentDidMount` in a functional component. The proper way is to use **Effect Hook** instead.

Let me share the below explanation from documentation:

&gt; If you’re familiar with React class lifecycle methods, you can think of useEffect Hook as componentDidMount, componentDidUpdate, and componentWillUnmount combined.

The below example also from documentation:

    import React, { useState, useEffect } from &#39;react&#39;;

    function Example() {
        const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

        // Similar to componentDidMount and componentDidUpdate:
        useEffect(() =&gt; {
            // Update the document title using the browser API
            document.title = `You clicked ${count} times`;
        });

        return (
            &lt;div&gt;
            &lt;p&gt;You clicked {count} times&lt;/p&gt;
            &lt;button onClick={() =&gt; setCount(count + 1)}&gt;
                Click me
            &lt;/button&gt;
            &lt;/div&gt;
        );
    }

So in summary you can fetch data by using `useEffect` hook in your code. Read further about how to use the **Effect Hook** [here][1].


  [1]: https://reactjs.org/docs/hooks-effect.html

You cannot use `componentDidMount` in a functional component. Use `useEffect` and pass an empty array to its dependencies, so it will work as a componentDidUpdate. For example:

 

     useEffect(() =&gt; {
            fetch(&quot;http://localhost:26854/api/premiershipteams&quot;)
                .then((response) =&gt; {
                    return response.json();
                })
                .then(data =&gt; {
                    let teamsFromApi = data.map(team =&gt; { return { value: team, display: team } })
                    this.setState({ teams: [{ value: &#39;&#39;, display: &#39;(Select your favourite team)&#39; }].concat(teamsFromApi) });
                }).catch(error =&gt; {
                    console.log(error);
                });
    }, []);

You can either turn your functional component into a class component, or read a little on react hooks in the [react documentation][1].


  [1]: https://reactjs.org/docs/hooks-effect.html

